SubTopics: Explain that differences in the apparent brightness of the sun compared to other stars is due to their relative distances from the Earth.
Content: The table shows some properties of three stars.
problems/TN23G5S/media/1a.jpg
Which conclusion is CORRECT based on the star data?

A.Choice: Rigel is the hottest, so it looks the dimmest from Earth.

B.Choice: The sun has the smallest diameter, so it looks the smallest from Earth.

C.Choice: Betelgeuse is farthest from Earth, so it looks the largest from Earth.

D.Choice: The sun is closest to Earth, so it looks the brightest from Earth.

SubTopics: Relate the tilt of the Earth's axis, as it revolves around the sun, to the varying intensities of sunlight at different latitudes. Evaluate how this causes changes in day-lengths and seasons.
Content: The diagram shows Earth at four points in its orbit around the sun. The dot on Earth represents the location of Tennessee.
problems/TN23G5S/media/2a.jpg
Tennessee has the same number of daylight hours and nighttime hours two times each year. At which two points in Earth's orbit does this occur?

SubTopics: Use evidence from the presence and location of fossils to determine the order in which rock strata were formed.
Content: The diagram shows two cliffs that are located very close to each other. Both cliffs have rock layers that contain fossils.
problems/TN23G5S/media/3a.jpg
Which statement correctly compares the ages of the rock layers?

A.Choice: Rock layer F is the same age as rock layer E.

B.Choice: Rock layer J is younger than rock layer D.

C.Choice: Rock layer B is the same age as rock layer A.

D.Choice: Rock layer A is older than rock layer G.

SubTopics: Analyze and interpret data from fossils to describe types of organisms and their environments that existed long ago. Compare similarities and differences of those to living organisms and their environments. Recognize that most kinds of animals (and plants) that once lived on Earth are now extinct.
Content: Scientists found a fossilized plant. The scientists compared features of the fossilized plant to four plants that are living today. The scientists determined the types of habitats where the plants that are living today grow.
problems/TN23G5S/media/4a.jpg
problems/TN23G5S/media/4b.jpg
Based on this information, which of these describes a habitat where the fossilized plant MOST LIKELY lived?

C.Choice: near the edge of a dry forest

SubTopics: Use evidence to construct an explanation for how variations in characteristics among individuals within the same species may provide advantages to these individuals in their survival and reproduction.
Content: Animals with light brown or gray fur tend to live in open, sunny areas. Animals with black fur tend to live in areas that are filled with shadows.
In which habitat would an animal with black fur MOST LIKELY survive better than an animal with light-colored fur?

A.Choice: a forest that has many trees growing close together

B.Choice: a desert that has deep sand and only a few plants

C.Choice: a tundra that has snow covering the ground and no growing plants

D.Choice: a mountain region that has evergreen trees spread far apart

SubTopics: Analyze and interpret data to show that the amount of matter is conserved even when it changes form, including transitions where matter seems to vanish.
Content: A student investigates sugar cubes by following the steps shown.

:box:• Measure the mass of an empty beaker.

• Measure the mass of three sugar cubes.

• Pour water into the beaker and measure the mass of the water and beaker.

• Add the three sugar cubes to the water in the beaker. Once the sugar cubes can no longer be seen, measure the mass of the beaker again.
problems/TN23G5S/media/6a.jpg
Which bar graph represents the amount of matter present after the sugar cubes can no longer be seen?

SubTopics: Evaluate the results of an experiment to determine whether the mixing of two or more substances result in a change of properties.
Content: Students combined substances in four investigations. Their data are shown in the table.
problems/TN23G5S/media/7a.jpg
Which investigation resulted in a change in the chemical properties of the substances?

SubTopics: Test the effects of balanced and unbalanced forces on the speed and direction of motion of objects.
Content: The diagram shows the forces in newtons (N) acting on a block that is not moving.
problems/TN23G5S/media/8a.jpg
Which TWO ways can the forces be changed so the block starts to move toward the right?

A.Choice: Increase the force pointing to the right.

B.Choice: Decrease the force pointing to the right.

D.Choice: Decrease the force pointing to the left.

E.Choice: Increase the force pointing to the left.

SubTopics: Make observations and measurements of an object's motion to provide evidence that a pattern can be used to predict future motion.
Content: Two students are on a seesaw during recess. When Student A is at ground level, Student B is two meters above the ground. When the seesaw is completely horizontal, each student is exactly one meter above the ground.
problems/TN23G5S/media/9a.jpg
When Student A is two meters above the ground, where is Student B?

D.Choice: one and a half meters above the ground

SubTopics: Use evidence to support that the gravitational force exerted by Earth on objects is directed toward the Earth's center.
Content: A student claims that people cannot live in Antarctica. He claims they would be upside down and fall off the surface of Earth.
problems/TN23G5S/media/10a.jpg
The student's claim is

A.Choice: correct, since Antarctica is on the bottom of Earth.

B.Choice: correct, since gravity pulls everything from north to south.

C.Choice: incorrect, since gravity pulls everything to Earth's center.

D.Choice: incorrect, since people living in Antarctica are held to the surface by the atmosphere.
